{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600532/1930120201/0528.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\nREPORT COMPILED\nON HALF HOLIDAYS\nr\nData About Ready for Pre\nsentation to Hoover by\nBudget Bureau.\nA comprehensive report obtained from\nGovernment department and establish\nments on the estimated cost of Satur\nday half holidays throughout the year\ncow is at the Bureau of the Budget\nvirtually ready for President Hoover.\nWith half-holiday legislation already\nhaving passed the Senate, and now on\nthe calendar in the House, organizations\nof Government workers plan to push\nthe matter.\nAt the time the bill was brought up\nfor House consideration objection was\nraised on account of the probable cost,\nand following this the President was\nrequested informally for more Informa\ntion.\nNow the information has been gath\nered by Joint co-operation of the Bureau\nof Efficiency and the Bureau of the\nBudget.\nStudy of Report Expected.\nAt the Bureau of the Budget there\nWas the usual secretiveness about this\nreport, as there is about anything which\nis being done for the President himself.\nIt was taken for granted, however, that\n.the report will be studied, and trans\nomitted with some dispatch to the White\nHouse. How and when President Hbo\nver will transmit it to Congress for the\n\u2022legislative body to take up in connec\ntion with the pending legislation re\nmained a question today.\nMeantime, the plans of 11 local\nunions here of the National Federation\nof Federal Employes went forward for\na meeting Thursday night at the In\nterior Department Auditorium in the\ninterests of the half holiday. The\nspeakers will be William Green, presi\ndent Os the American Federation of\nLabor, and Representative John W. Mc-\nCormack of Massachusetts.\nS 6 Answer Questionnaire.\nFurther evidence that half holidays\non Saturdays are favored among the\nState governments was offered today\nby William R. Vallance, president of\nth% Federal Bar Association, which is\nsupporting the half-holiday legislation.\nThe Federal Bar Association sent out a\nquestionnaire to all the States and has\nheard from 36. Out of these States, 34\ngive half holidays to their State gov\nernment employes. New Mexico grants\nSaturday half holiday during the three\nSummer months and Texas gives a\nSaturday half holiday to one half of\neach department, so that every one\ngets half of his Saturday half holidays\nthroughout the year.\nMRS. KEITH MILLER,\nSAFE IN BAHAMAS,\nDESCRIBES FLIGHT\n{Continued From First Page.)\nwoman, who lived alone with a child.\nCommissioner Forsyth, at Andros Is\nland, she continued, helped her obtain\na small boat to bring her to Nassau\nyesterday to dispatch messages to her\nmother in New York and to friends.\nMiami aviation circles remained puz\nzled today, pending arrival of Mrs.\nKeith Miller at the alt* of her landing,\n12S miles or more south by east of her\nannounced destination. Aviators re\ncalled that A 30-mlle-an-hour wind was\nblowing from the east Friday when\nMrs. Keith Miller left Havana. They\npointed that except far unusual circum\nstances she would have been blown to\nthe west, probably over the Gulf of\nMexico, if the course deviated.\nInformation from Havana was that\nshe set a 34-degree course directly for\nMiami when she left and made no al\nlowance for wind drift.\nRefueling Plane Takes Off.\nMIAMI, Fla., December 2 (JP). \u2014Capt.\nW. N. Lancaster took off at 8:15 a.m.\ntoday for Nassau, Bahamas, to refuel\nthe plane for Mrs. J. M. Keith-Mlller\nand return the ship and the Australian\navlatrlk to this country.\nCourageous Mother Awaits.\nNEW YORK. December 2 (JP).\u2014' The\ncourageous mother of a flying daughter\ntoday awaited her return from the\nBahamas.\nMrs. E. M. L. Beveridge, mother of\nMrs. J. M. Kelth-Miller, ended a soli\ntary four-day vigil last night when she\nreceived this message: \u201cSafe. Notify\nfriends. Love. Jessie.\u201d\nMrs. Beveridge, the widow of a Mel\nbourne banker, said she expected her\ndaughter would start for New York at\nonce and then go to Pittsburgh, where\nher adventure started on November 22.\nmachadTreinstates\nCUBAN CONSTITUTION\nMartial Law Lifted in Havana Two\nDay* Before Expiration of\nTime Decreed.\nBr the Associated Press.\nHAVANA, December 2.\u2014-Constitu\ntional guarantees were reinstated yes\nterday by order of President Machado,\ntwo days before the expiration of the\noriginal 20-day period authorized by\nCongress. With martial law lifted Ha\nvana last night appeared more tranquil\nthan at any time in several months.\nThe President has been authorized to\nsuspend constitutional guarantees all\nover the island for 60 days more, but it\nis believed that he will not find this\nt necessary.\nThe President also authorized the\nreopening Wednesday of the National\nUniversity, Havana normal schools and\nthe School of Commerce at Santa\nClara, all of which had been closed for\nseveral weeks as the result of student\ndisorders.\nThe Spanish language newspaper El\nPais says that the economic commis\nsion, appointed by President Machado\nto unravel Cuba\u2019s financial tangle, was\ncontemplating ways and means of con\nsolidating the republic's indebtedness\nby borrowing $250,000,000 to cancel its\nshort-term loans.\nThe consolidation proposal has been\ndiscussed Informally several times, but\nit has been denied that the plan has\nbeen given serious consideration.\nNAVY BUILDING HALT\nMAY END THIS MONTH\nSpokesman Says Arrangements Not\nHade to Extend French-\nItalian Holiday,\n\nBy the Associated Press.\nPARIS, December 2.\u2014-A government\nspokesman said today that no arrange\nment had been made with Italy con\ncerning prolongation of the navsl build\ning holiday which, France understands,\nextends through this month.\nShould conversation* encouraged by\nAmbassador Gibson, the American, not\nreach a successful conclusion soon, it\nwas pointed out, tome decision must\nbe reached as to whether the holiday\naccepted by Brtgnd and Mussolini will\ni.jte continued,\nA-\nBICENTENNIAL PLAN PROGRESS]\nSHOWN BY VIGOROUS CAMPAIGN\nV.\nRepresentative Bloom Lists Many Ste\u00a3s\nAlready Taken Toward (7oal, in 1932, of\n\u201cHumanizing\u201d George Washington.\nFrom Its national headquarters In\nthe Washington Building the George\nWashington Bicentennial Commission\nIs vigorously prosecuting a compre\n\u2022hensive program designed to reach out\nand bring to every State and territory,\nevery county, city and town of the\ncountry, a series of celebrations In\n1932, which will vividly 'reach every\nindividual in the whole country with\na clear picture of the Father of his\ncountry, the Inspiration of his example,\nthe power of his Influence upon the\nUnited States today.\n\u201cWe want to humanize Washington,\u201d\ndeclared Representative Sol Bloom, as\nsociate director of the commission, \u201cand\nbring him right down to the people.\u201d\nPlan Great Thanksgiving.\nThe gigantic bicentennial will have\nIts principal functions here In the Cap.\nltal of the Nation. It will begin on\nWashington\u2019s birthday, February 22,\n1932, with a stirring ceremony, the\nnature of which has not yet been di\nvulged. It will conclude with another\ngreat ceremony on Thanksgiving day,\n1932, when the whole American people,\nin a series of services throughout the\nland, will give thanks for George\nWashington.\nThe whole comprehensive program\nhas not only been mapped out with\nclarity, according to Mr. Bloom, and\nwith great attention to detail, but it\nis being pushed forward with alacrity,\nso that the whole American people\nmay be caught up in the acceleration\nof spiritual awakening to the noble ex\nample of Washington. As event follows\nevent throughout the year, ns the great\nness of Washington reaches the indi\nvidual through Innumerable channels\nof approach, it Is the confident feel\nt ing of the Bicentennial Commision\nthat the American people as a whole\nwill be quickened in spirit and uplifted\nin soul.\nGreat Movie Planned.\nAmong the features planned for the\nbicentennial, one of the highly interest\ning developments is expected to swing\ninto accomplishment within a few\ndays, when motion picture cameramen\nof the Eastman Teaching Films, Inc.,\nwith a staff of experts, arrive in Wash\nington to begin filming the big motion\npicture of \u201cThe Life of Washington.\u201d\nGeorge Eastman, president of the East\nman Kodak Co. and of the Eastman\nTeaching Films, Inc., Is a member of\nthe Washington Bicentennial Commis\nsion, and Is keenly interested in bring\ning Washington to the people In as\nvivid a manner as possible. The motion\npicture, which is becoming of greatly\nincreasing value, through more pro\njectors In the school houses and the\nhomes of the land, as well as the count\nless theaters. Is to be utilized as a\nhighly helpful factor in the big program\nto bring Washington to every person In\nte land.\nIndlcatfbns also point to the making\nof a motion picture of the history of the\nDistrict of Columbia. This ts under\nstood to be arranged to show the his\ntoric development of the Capital City,\nits great public buildings and various\nfunctions of government. Thus the\npeople will get a more perfect picture\nof the great Capital of the Nation, bear\ning the name of George Washington.\nEastman to Pay Coat.\nThe motion picture of the life of\nWashington, which is to be started\nwithin a few days, has been Arranged\nin co-operation with the Eastman\nKodak Co. educational service, which\nwill defray the cost of making tne pic\nture. It will make use of sound and\ncolor, and will Include actusd scenes\non the Mount Vernon estate. The gen\neral -Aim will be in many reels and ap\npropriately arranged, so that programs\nmay be made up of varying lengths, and\nthe reels themselves will be available\nfor schools, churches, patriotic organ\nizations and clubs throughout the\nUnited States, and may be shown also\nIn motion picture theaters.\nThe general program of the Bicen\ntennial Commission begins with th,\nchildren In kindergarten and carries on\nup through the schools and colleges,\npatriotic and fraternal organizations,\nchurches, business houses, town, city\nand State organizations spreading to\nan organization beyond the seas, in\nEurope.\nState Co-operation Sought.\nThe scope of the work of the com\nmission is depicted graphically on a\nlarge map of the United States in the\ncommission\u2019s headquarters. The official\nco-operation of the State governments\nis not only being solicited and checked\nby a system of colored pins but is being\nfollowed up assiduously to obtain such\nofficial co-operation. Associate Director\nBloom feels that substantial progress in\nthis direction is being made, but the\nStates are being pushed to Join in\nfurther. A blue button on the map\nshows where States have authorized and\nappointed State commissions; a black\nand white pin shows appropriation\nauthorized; a yellow button shews that\na commission has been authorized by\nthe Legislature, but not appointed; a\nred button, that no action has yet been\ntaken by the Legislature or Governor;\na green button, the State refuses to\nparticipate, and a white button, Gov\nernor\u2019s representative or citizens\u2019 com\nmittee appointed.\nA great mass of manuscript is being\nprepared in various parts of the com\nmission\u2019s headquarters, to be available\nfor use by persons in all manner of\ncelebrations from the kindergarten on\nup. Hundreds of these manuscripts\nhave already been completed and others\nare under way, as the writers produce\ndocuments, to be carefully checked by\nthe official historir.n of the commission\nbefore being issued to the public.\nGovernors Make Appeal.\nMailbags full of mall flow steadily out\nof the headquarter\", consigned to all\ncomers of the country and to all man\nner of Individuals and organizations.\nThe commission, In accordance with\nIts elaborate program, Is supplying in\nformation to newspapers, magazines and\nall kinds of periodicals.\nAlready the Governors of all the\nStates have delivered radio appeals\nthrough leading radio stations of the\ncountry explaining the celebration and\nsoliciting support of their own people.\nPageants for local celebrations are in\nthe course of preparation and will de\nplct historic scenes and incidents in the\nlife of Washington for large and small\ni groups of players. In similar fashion\npageants and plays for schools and col\nleges are being prepared so that every\nschool, both public and private, in the\nUnited States may put on appropriate\ni pageants and plays.\nThe committee on selection of ah\nauthentic picture of Washington has\nnarrowed the field of portraits down\nto two or three. Within a short time\nthe one picture authorized as present\ning the best judgment of this commit\ntee and of the directors will be chosen,\nand prints in color or In black and\nwhite will be sent to every school in\nthe United States.\n1 History Being Compiled.\nA history of the various historic\npaintings of Washington, as well as of\nthe more famous busts and statues\nof Washington, is being compiled\nand is to be authenticated bjr the\nhistorical authorities of the commission,\nt headed by Dr. Albert Bushneli Hart\nof Harvard, who already has passed\nupon a great mass of manuscript.\nWithin the past few months tne first\nand second volumes of a series of sp\nproximately 25 volumes of the definitive\nwritings of George Washington have\nbeen compiled and are in the hands\nK of the Government Printing Office,\nt These writings represent the complete\nt writings of George Washington and,\nt fully naif of them have never before\nf appeared in print, or at least in any\n1 work of similar character as that now\nundertaken,\nTHE EVENING iSTAR. WASHINGTON. D. C- TUESDAY. DECEMBER 2, 1930.\nThis series to be published by the\nGovernment as a memorial edition rep\nresents a tremendous amount of re\nsearch and the work is under the direc\ntion of Dr. John C. Fitzpatrick of the\nLibrary of Congress. The publication\nwill be available for distribution to all\npublic libraries In the United States, as\nwell as to Individuals who wish to pur\nchase them.\nMaps to Show Travels.\nA series of atlases and maps show\ning the travels of Washington is being\nprepared.\nThousands of letters have been writ\nten and responses have been generously\nreceived from organizations of various\nkinds, who are asked to incorporate\nWashington celebrations into their 1932\nsessions. Special material is being pre\npared for use in county and State fairs\nthroughout the country, where \"George\nWashington, the Farmer\u201d will be\nstressed. Special attention is being\ngiven to the presentation of Washing\nton In his fraternal affiliations. The\nassociate directors. Mr. Bloom, and Col.\nU. S. Grant, 3d, who has resigned, have\nheld meetings with prominent Masonic\nbodies, and are working with the grand\nlodges of Virginia and the District of\nColumbia in the development of a great\nprogram in connection with the dedi\ncation of the George Washington Ma\nsonic Memorial at Alexandria in 1932.\nNumerous other activities Include in\nstructions for libraries throughout the\ncountry, radio plays and pageants, dis\nplays for department stores, instruc\ntions for readings about George Wash\nington, programs for women\u2019s or\nganizations. a series of 16 pamphlets,\nunder direction of Dr. Hart. \u201cHonor to\nGeorge Washington,\u201d about half of\nwhich are completed; special printed\nmaterial suggested, such as calendars,\nwith some of the foremost calendar\nmanufacturers already planning Wash\nington Illustrations; telegraph blanks in\n1932 of the great companies will bear\npictures of Washington and appropriate\nreierence to the celebration. Many\ngreat business organizations, such as\nthe American Telephone Telegraph\nCo., are now printing special material\nto be broadcast to millions In 1932 In\nthe form of bulletins, pamphlets, letters,\npictures an\u00a3 other matter, such as post\ners and banners. Many corporations are\nplanning a line on their stationery call\ning attention to Jhe celebration.\nOld Firms to Take Part.\nTwo hundred and ten business houses\nnow active, which were in business in\nWashington's time, have been asked to\ntell the principles of success which have\ncarried them through the long span of\nyears.\nThrough co-operation with music\npublishers, there Is being compiled a\nlist of the songs, marches and melodies\nof Colonial days, which will be avail\nable.\nThe National Education Association\nhas agreed to assist in bringing the\nWashington program into the schools\nof the country.\nThe Bureau of Engraving, it was an\nnounced by the commission, is now\nworking on designs for a series of com\nmemorative postage stamps. A special\ncommittee is designing a commemora\ntive medal..\nListing briefly a few of the additional\nactivities of the commission. Mr. Bloom\nreferred to co-operative work with for\neign societies in the United States; co\noperation with patriotic societies; gen\neral loan exhibit; pamphlet on historic\nsites; publications for the blind, and\nslides for use in clubs, lodges, patriotic\norganizations and schools.\nIn all the activities of this Govern\nment commission, Mr. Bloom em\nphasized, the commercial element Is\nexcluded.\nMRS. JOHN A. DOUGHERTY\nINJURED AT GRID GAME\nProminent Member of D. C. Society\nIs Recuperating in Chicago\nHospital.\n(Prom the 5:30 Edition ol Yesterday\u2019s Star\nMrs. JohA Allen Dougherty, prom\ninent in Washington society circles, was\nslightly injured at Soldier Field Sta\ndium In Chicago after the close of the\nNotre Dame-Army foot ball game Sat\nurday, when throngs of spectators jam\nmed their way out of the stadium, ac\ncording to word received here.\nMrs. Dougherty was taken to St.\nLuke\u2019s Hospital for treatment and Is\nrecuperating there. She expects to re\nturn to Washington within a few days.\n.She makes her home here at the May\nflower Hotel. Friends here have re\nceived word that she was not Injured\nseriously.\nROUND-UP NTrS 75\nDry Agents Expect to Seize 50\nMore in Coast Drive.\nHOQUfAM, Wash., December 2 UP).\n\u2014Seventy-five persons were under ar\nrest at Gray\u2019s Harbor today, and more\narrests were expected in a general\nround-up by Federal prohibition agents.\nOnly small quantities of liquor were\nseized.\nOs the 60 arraigned yesterday, many\nwere placed under SI,OOO bond. A store\nbuilding 'was rented for the arraign\nments. Agents said they expected to\nmake 50 more arrests here, in Aber\ndeen and Coemopolis. Federal officers\nhad been operating here for months\nin the guise of loggers.\n\nNewly Appointed\nCabinet Member\nMust Await Vote\nSecretary and Mrs. Doak\nVisit Labor Department\nand Greet Callers.\nBy the Associated Press.\nShe Is rot yet a cabinet lady, but\nMrs. William N. Doak already has dem\nonstrated some of the abilities she will\nbe called on to use when her husband\ntakes his place as Secretary of Labor.\nWhen Doak appeared at the Labor\nDepartment yesterday to take over his\nnew duties, only to find he had to\nawait Senate confirmation, Mrs. Doak\nwas with him, mixing with the labor\nleaders, shaking hands and receiving\nmessages from far States where she\nhad appeared with her husband.\n\u201cI know all these men almost as well\nas he does,\u201d she said. \u201cWe\u2019ve worked\namong them for almost 30 years.\u201d\nHaving no children to keep her\nanchored to one spot, Mrs. Doak, a\nsmall, amiling, feminine figure with\ncurly blonde hair and blue eyea, has\ntraveled far and wide.\nI For 10 years, her home was a Wash\nington hotel, her life there the whirl\nof politics mingled with the social chat\nwhich always accompanies such sessions,\nj Then the hearth-love within Mrs.\nDoak had its day. She found a rural\nretreat where she could cook, sew, grow\nflowers In general and a rose garden\nin particular, and raise chickens.\nOn the lofty Potomac palisades above\ni Washington, close to Chain Bridge,\nrendezvous of Capital picknlckers, the\nDoaks built a huge white stucco home,\nl and kennel for their pedigreed Bcotch\ncollies, pure white. That was five years\nago.\nr \u201cI raised 300 chickens this year. I lost\nonly a fey.\u201d Mrs, Dealt said proudly.\nHOSPITAL REPORTS\nPAINT INCREASE\nDirectors of Children\u2019s Insti\ntution Elect Board Mem\nbers for Ensuing Year.\nReports showing marked Increases In\nthe number of patients treated at Chil\ndren's Hospital In 1930 and outlining\nother activities of the Institution were j\nmade at the sixtieth annual meeting\nof the hospital\u2019s board of directors yes- J\nterday afternoon. Election of board\nmembers for the ensuing year also\nfeatured the meeting.\nJames M. Green, a member of the\nboard, presided. The report of Thomas\nB. Sweeney on the hospital, made a\nnumber of recommendations for Im\nprovements. It was read by Dr. John\nA. Talbot,\nThe report of the medical staff, read\nby Dr. Frank Leech showed the hospital\ntreated 5,147 children In 1930, as com\npared to 3,796 In 1929. The number of\nhospital days was practically the same\nand Dr. Leech explained that this Is\ndue to increased equipment which\nenables the staff to furnish medical\ncare at a faster rate than in 1929.\nLack Finances for Work.\nCuno H. Rudolph, president of the\nhospital, read the report on recommen\ndations made by Dr. Bachmeyer. who\nassisted in making the recent health\nand hospital survey for the Council of\nSocial Agencies, at the request of the\nCommunity Chest, and said that the\nChildren's Hospital would be glad to\ncarry them all out except for the one\nmatter of finances.\nMrs. Frederick H. Brooke read the\nreport of the Ladies\u2019 Board: Mrs. Anson\nPhelps Stokes that of the Child Welfare\nSociety; Mrs. Cary T. Grayson the're\nport of Social Service Work of the\nJunior League and Mrs. Frank Hight\ngave a report of the Thrift Shop.\nResolutions of respect to the memories\nof Mrs. John Crayke Simpson and Myer\nCohen, board members, who di**d during\nthe past year, were read by Mrs. Brooke\nand Col. Arthur O'Brien. Election of\nboard members followed.\nThe following are the permanent\nmembers of the board;\nMrs. Frederick Brooke, George W.\nBrown, Admiral W. H. Brownson, H.\nLandon Burchell. Mrs. James F. Cur\ntis, Senator James Couzens, Dr. Edgar\nCopeland, Henry P. Fairbanks, Fred\nerick de C. Faust, C. C. Glover, James\nM. Green, Frank C. Henry, Frank S\u00bb\nHight, O. H. P. Johnson, James B.\nLambie. Marshall Langhome, Mrs. Louis\nC. Lehr, Dr. Frank Leech. Henry S.\nMatthews, Miss Virginia Miller, Mrs.\nFrank B. Noyes, Col. Arthur O\u2019Brien,\nW. M. Ritter, Cuno H. Rudolph, Mrs.\nStanley Rinehart, B. F. Saul. Henry\nSheridan, Mrs. Irene Sheridan, Thomas\nB. Swenev, Dr. John A. Talbot, Fred\neric William Wile and Dr.\u2018Joseph S.\nWall.\nPersonnel of the Board.\nThe following annual members, who,\nwith the permanent members, consti\ntute the board, were elected:\nMiss Mary B. Adams. Comdr. Paul\nBastedo, Mrs. W. H. Brownson, Miss\nAlice J. Clapp. E. F. Colladay, Karl\nCorby. Mrs. Whitman Cross, Mrs. John\nAllan Dougherty, Charles Drayton. Mat\nthews Dick, Victor Deyber, John Eynon,\nMrs. Stephen B. Elkins, Mrs. William C.\nEustis, C. F. Fadely, Mrs. Annie A.\nFendall, Mrs. Sallie C. Fendall, J. C.\nFlannery, Mrs. W. J. Flather, jr.; Sher\nman Flint, Dr. John A. Foote, G. W.\nForsberg. Julius Garflnckel, Mrs. C. C.\n1 Glover, C. C. Glover, jr.; Samuel Greer,\nGeorge E. Hamilton, J. T. Hendrick, Rev.\nJohn H. Hollister, Harrison Howe, Dr.\nGeorge C. Havenner, A. B. Houghton,\nWilliam Hibbs, Frank J. Hogan, Mrs.\nBeale R. Howard. Mrs. Walter Hutch\nins, Walter Hutchins, Charles C. Jones,\nR. M. Kauffmann, Mrs. Victor Kauff\nmanh, Dr. Harry Hyland Kerr, Miss\nBessie Kibbey, Dr. George M. Kober,\nMrs. Ridley McLean, H. W. Mil\nler, Mrs. Geneva B. Nairn, Mrs. John\nNewbold. E. C. Owen, Mrs. Ross Perry,\nDr. Stanley Rinehart, Mrs. Edith Nourse\nRogers, Mrs. Cuno H. Rudolph, H. L.\nRust, H. L. Rust, Jr., Mrs. B. F. Saul, Miss\nJulia D. Smoot, Charles P. Stone, L.\nCorrln Strong, Mrs. Louis Titus, Charles\nH. Tompkins, Dr. Reginald Walker,\nHorace Westcott, Nathan Weill, Charles\nWoodhull, Senator Lawrence C. Phipps,\nC. Melvin Sharpe, William S. Qulntcr,\nCapt. John Gibbons and S. T. Cameron.\nDAVIS IS SEATED\nAS SENATE VOTES\nDOWN NYE MOVE\nFrom First Page.)\nby and In behalf of senatorial candi\ndates In those States where the suc\ncessful candidates begin service in this\nbody at this, the short session, of the\nSeventy-first Congress.\n\u201cThese States are New Jersey, Dela\nware, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Tennessee,\nKentucky, Kansas and Wyomsig. On\nDecember 4 the committee will conduct\na*hearlng, at which time, further New\nJersey testimony will be taken, as a\nresult of which the committee expects\nto be able to report finally. In the\ncase of all the other States named, with\none possible exception, the committee\nis confident that its report could not\npossibly serve as the basis for any ob\njection to the Senators-elect from those\nStates being administered the oath of\noffice and accorded a place in this body.\n\u201cThe one possible exception Is that\nof Pennsylvania, which State has issued\ncredentials of election to James J. Davis.\nIt is to this one case that this special\nreport is directed.\u201d\nDavis Issues Statement.\nIn the light of existing conditions,\nDavis last night issued the following\nstatement:\n\u201cI was informed that Senator Ny#'\nwished to study further the matter of\ncontributions in the recent Pennsyl\nvania election. After consultation with\nSenate Republican leaders, who had\nalso conferred with Senator Nye, it\nseemed to me best to withhold by cre\ndentials until Chairman Nye had time\nto make his examination, that is, until\ntomorrow.\n\u201cIn the meantime I desire to state\nthat having nothing whatever to con\nceal I fully court whatever further in\nvestigation Senator Nye cares to make\nand will co-operate with him and the\ncommittee.\u201d\nThe Secretary\u2019s resignation was made\neffective today. In accepting it, the\nPresident, in a letter made public late\nyesterday, thanked Mr. Davis \"for the\nmanner in which you have conducted\nthe Department of Labor for a period\ni of nearly 10 years.\u201d\nPredicts Return of Prosperity.\nIn his letter of resignation, Davis re\nminded Mr. Hoover that they had\nentered the cabinet of President Hard\ning together in 1921. \u201cat a time of\ndepression far greater than that through\nwhich we are now passing and we came\nout of it into the greatest prosperity\nin the history of the country.\u201d\n\"Under your guidance we will emerge\nfrom the present depression into a\nprosperity as great as the one before,\u201d\nhe said.\nMr. Hoover said in his reply that he\nregarded it \u201cas fortunate, indeed, that\nthe country is still to retain your service\nin the Senate.\u201d\nDoak, meanwhile, was without official\nstatus. Yesterday he had gone through\nthe form of taking the oath of office,\nbut this was termed \u201cmerely a rehear\nsal\u201d later in the day. Congress was in\nsession, the Davis resignation was not\nyet in effect, and the President\u2019s power\nof making appointments withput Senate\nconfirmation had lapsed for another\nthree months.\nIn the meantime, Robe Carl White,\nthe Assistant Secretary of Labor, will\nbe Acting Secretary.\nTHE HOUSE HEARS THE PRESIDENT\u2019S MESSAGE\ni\" 11 11\nI Sit 88 88 jwp hhhhh\nHa c Hit St 8 SS aMHDH\nmm SgSjgF Ej& BB ESE& JBg h JbBBB\nPatrick J. Haltigan, reading clerk of the House, reading the annual*communlcation from the White House this morning.\n\u2014A. P. Photo.\nPOLLARD IS HIT\nBT UNION GROUPS\nCold Weather Descends on\nDanville Area as Strike\nPickets Resume Patrols.\n\nSpecial Dispatch to The \u00a3tar.\nDANVILLE. Va., December 2.\u2014With\ncontinued orderliness in the Schoolfleld\nsti ike area, a battle of words raged to\nday In an offensive against officialdom\nwhich brought troops to Schoolfleld and\nwhich union officials fear will crush the\nstrike by oppression.\nThe Virginia Federation of Labor at\ntacked Gov. Pollard for his troop order\non five counts, referring among other\nthings to charges filed against Col. H.\nL. Opie in command of the troops here\nduring the World War, during which\nthe military commander was awarded\nthe Distinguished Service Medal.\nUnion Canvasses Merchants.\nThe local union backed up the fed\neration by Issuing a statement to the\neffect that a large number of mer\nchants and business men of Danville\nhad been shown by canvass not to be\nin sympathy with resolutions adopted\nSaturday condemning the strike and\ncommending the Governor for bring\ning troops here.\nCol. Opie himself would not refer to\ncharges brought against him after the\nWorld War, but Capt. M. T. Warner,\nhis adjutant, issued a statement re\nferring to \u201cempty charges\u201d follow\u2019ing\nthe \u201chysteria of war\u201d and called atten\ntion to the fact that the Virginia Sen\nate records show that Opie was com\npletely exonerated of all of them.\nCold Weather Hits Area.\nCold weather swept down on the mill\narea today, the very day the union pick\nets went back on duty, denied the right\nto use fires.\nLindsey W. Moore of Pittsylvania\nCounty, former Washington and Lee\nfoot ball ace, a brother of \"County\u201d\nMoore of the Annapolis team some years\nago, and former military burgomaster of\nWiesbaden during the American occu\npation of Germany, and who has been\nappointed to be the \u201cMussolini\u201d of the\nSchoolfleld police, under orders of Judge\nTurner Clement, began preparing for his\nnew position as special chief of police\ntoday.\nA force of 50 civilian police, most of\nthem former service men, is to be se\nlected and function independently of,\nbut in co-operation with, the sheriff\u2019s\nforces. This action was taken yester\nday by the Pittsylvania County Board\nof Supervisors in the face* of charges of\na \"breakdown\u201d in the present county\nforces, resulting, it is alleged, in disor\nders which caused troops to be sent here.\n\nCONGRESS IS READY\nFOR SERIOUS WORK\nAWAITING ITS ACTION\n(Continued From First Page.)\nbuildings and highway programs au\nthorized in the last session of Congress,\nRobinson's measure would authorize\nthe issuance of notes or bonds, if neces\nsary, to provide funds. The Glenn bill\nwould make no provisions for raising\nmoney.\nMeanwhile the bill \"basket in the\nHouse was crowded with similar meas\nures.\nRepresentative Aswell, Democrat.\nLouisiana, proposed to authorize SOO,-\n000,00 for feed and seed loans to farm\ners. Chairman Haugen of the House\nAgriculture Committee, announced he\nwould call a meeting before the end\nof the week to consider this measure.\nWould Pay Bonus.\nA bill to remove the $15,000-a-mile\nlimitation on Federal aid highway con\nstruction was proposed by Represent\native Treadway, Republican, Massachu\nsetts.\nRepresentative McLeod, Republican,\nMichigan, introduced one proposing\nImmediate payment of the soldiers'\nbonus by a $4,000,000,000 bond issue.\nAnother by Representative Clancy, Re\npublican, Michigan, would reduce the\ninterest rate on adjusted compensation\ncertificates from 6 to 4 per cent.\nA bill to provide for the expenditure\nof $500,000,000 in two years for road\nconstruction was Introduced by Repre\nsentative Browne, Republican, Wiscon\nsin. He proposed half of it should be\nspent on truck roads, over which farm\ners haul their produce. His measure\nwould Increase the Federal contribution\nfrom 50 to 80 per cent, leaving the\nStates only 20 per cent.\nOther Bills Offered.\nAmong other Measures to provide\nemergency relief and prevent future\nbusiness depressions were:\nBy Representative Ludlow. Democrat,\nIndiana, to create a Federal Industrial\nCommission tc stabilize employment.\nBy Representative Kelly, Republican,\nPennsylvania, to appropriate $10,000,-\n000 for public building construction.\nBy Representative Edith Nourse Rog\ners, Republican, Massachusetts, to au\nthorize $52,000,000 for veterans\u2019 hospital\nconstruction.\nLYLE VOTECONTESTED\nCHICAGO. 111.. December 2 up.\nFormer Municipal Judge Charles F.\nMcKinley filed suit In Circuit Court\nyesterdav to contest the election of\nthree m .icipal judges, including John\nH. Lyle, the terror of gangland.\nMcKi ey charges gross errors and\ncommls on* and fraudulent collusion\nof elect on judges and clerks.\nVictim of Hold-up,\nDisgusted, Turns\nAnd Beats Robber\nBr the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. December 2.\nManuel Ramme, undertaker, was\ncounting his money last night,\nputting S2OO in his vest pocket\nand $1.07 in his trousers, when a\nrobber walked In and Ramme\nyielded to the pressure of a pistol.\nWhen the hold-up noth\ning but $1.07 Ramme was so dis\ngusted With his technique that he\nwhirled suddenly, took the weapon\nfrom him, beat him on the head\nwith it and then called police.\nThe prisoner refused to give his\nname.\nYEGGS TAKE KB\nFROM POST OFFICE\nProfessional Robbers Sus\npected of Cracking Safe\nLast Night at Annapolis.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nANNAPOLIS, Md., December 2.\u2014Thl\npoet office at Annapolis was robbed last\nnight of stamps and money estimated\nat from SB,OOO to SIO,OOO by a party of\nrobbers numbering two or more, who\nwere evidently professionals. They en\ntered the building by Jimmying a side\nwindow and opened the safe by the use\nof an acetelyne apparatus an*- nitro\nglycerin. Tim tanks used by the robbers\nwere left in the building.\nIt is believed that the robbery took\nplace between midnight and 3 o'clock\nthis morning, as it was noticed that the\nlight which usually burns through the\nnight was out during that period.\nThe robbery was discovered by J.\nKent Worthington, a clerk, who went\non duty at 5:30 o\u2019clock this morning.\nWorthington informed the postmaster,\nJoseph M. Armstrong, of what had hap\npened, and Armstrong in turn notified\nPost Office Inspector Harry L. Conner,\nwho reached Annapolis at an early hour\nand took charge of the investigation.\nOuter Door Burned.\nMarks of the tools used to open the\nwindow by which the robbers entered\ncan be seen plainly on the sill. They\nsucceeded in breaking the catch which\nheld the window, readily entering the\nbuilding at a point near the safe.\nThe heavy outer door of the safe\nwas opened by heat of the torch. A\nbar running from the lock was com\npletely destroyed by means of the in\ntense heat, permitting the handle of\nthe door to turn freely.\nAs they opened the safe door the\nrobbers encountered an inner door,\nwhich they opened by blowing the lock\nwith nitroglycerin. The wires and\nexploded fuse were left by the door\nand there were marks on the door\nevidently caused by the explosion.\nInside of the vault the main safe was\nfound, but it was protected by a burglar\nproof lock and apparently the burglars\nmade no effort to open it. However,\nthey opened five compartments pro\ntected by light metal doors and which\ncontained stamps and cash charged to\nthe different clerks.\nFour of the compartments were open\ned with the torch and one by the use\nof a key.\nLoss Fixed at SB,OOO.\nTlie robbers secured the whole amount\nof their plunder by rifling these com\npartments. Each clerk at the post\noffice is assigned a certain amount of\nstamps and at the end of the day\u2019s\nbusiness returns his stamps intact to\nhis own compartment.\nThis system makes it possible to as\ncertain the exact amount of the loas.\nIt is estimated that this will be at least\nSB,OOO. Exact figures will be given out\nlater in the -day.\nThere is also a possible clue in the\nfact.that a substantial portion of the\nloot constated of books and 1 and 2 cent\nstamps, which may be difficult for the\nrobbers to handle.\nINVENTOR CLAIMS NEW DEVICE\nELIMINATES CARBON MONOXIDE\nFormer Edison Engineer Demonstrates Instrument to\nCapt. Hawks and Others.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, December 2.\u2014Out of\nthe death of an airplane pilot in 1928\nhas come a device which its Inventor\nclaims will eliminate carbon monoxide\nfumes from gasoline engines and save\nmore than $1,000,000,000 annually in'\nthe Nation's fuel bills.\nDr. Miller Reese Hutchison, chief en\ngineer for Thomas A. Edison from 1909\nto 1918, and originator of the Klaxon\nand the acousticon, demonstrated the\ninvention yesterday before Capt. Frank\nM. Hawks, flying speed king, and others.\nThe Instrument, known as the \u201cMoto-\nVita,\u201d was developed primarily to in\ncrease the efficiency and flight range\nof airplanes, as the result of the acci\ndental death of Dr. Hutchison\u2019s son,\nHarold, an airplane pilot It employs\nthe principle of catalysis to prevent the\nSPIED FOR FRENCH\nRED PLOnER SAYS\n\nPassed Along Information on\nIndustries, Ramsin Tells\nMoscow Court.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMOSCOW, December 2. Leonid\nRamsin, \u201carch plotter\" of the eight men\non trial here for working to overthrow\nthe Soviet government, today told how\nhe and his men spied on Soviet in\ndustries and passed their information\nalong through devious channels to the\nofficers of the French general staff.\nThis happened in the trial where the\nfour judges ruled only a few days ago\nthat there would be no more mention\nof \u201cfriendly foreign governments.\u201d\nThrough the mysterious agents iden\ntified by the letters, K, A and R, said\nRamsin, he and his associates passed\nevery kind of information they could\nabout the Soviet industrial develop\nment to a \u201ccertain French institution\nin Moscow.\u201d\nThe only \u201cFrench institution\u201d in the\nSoviet capital is the French embassy.\nThe defendants admitted today that\nmost of their spying was done for the\nFrench, but they insisted that an es\npionage organization existed among the\nengineers in Soviet Russia for many\nyears before this plot was organized.\nTold to Cripple Railways.\n\u201cMost of the instructions from Paris,\u201d\nsaid, Ramsin. \u201ccame from \u2018K.\u2019 They\nwere demands for industrial informa\ntion and for facts about military activ\nities. We were instructed to disable\nmilitary and electrical Industries and\nto cripple the railways at every op\nportunity. In this conection our sug\ngestions were approved by \u2018R.\u2019\u201d\nThe prosecutor, N. B. Krilenko, has\ndrawn from each of the eight on trial\ndetails of fantastic efforts to under\nmine the Russian industrial and\neconomic structure.\nCharnovsky, one of the defendants,\nyesterday listed two sabotage schemes\nwhich failed. One involved purchase of\nlocomotives with a weight of 35 tons\non each axle. Engines of this weight\nwould have been so heavy that all rail\nway bridges would'have had to be re\nbuilt at enormous expense. The other\nwas to install automatic couplings on\nrailway cars.\nFalsified Estimates.\nKalinikov, another of the defendants,\nrelated how he had falsified estimates\nas to Russia\u2019s potential iron output for\n1927 and 1928, although admitting that\nhis figures were not accepted. He also\ntold of sabotage activities in the chemi\ncal, lumber, paper and cement indus\ntries.\nProf. Leonid Ramsin, leader of the\ndefendants, said the Industrial party,\nto which they all belonged, did not\nspecify forms of sabotage to be prac\nticed, but gave members a general idea,\nfrom which they developed their own\nschemes. x\n\nFOUNTAIN IS DEDICATED\nIN JEWISH FOSTER HOME\nMrs. Gus Louis Unveils \u201cSpirit of\nLife,\u201d Erected in Memory of\nMrs. Solomon Herzog.\nA marble and bronze fountain, de\npicting the \u201cspirit of. life,\u201d erected in\nthe recreation room of the Jewish Fos\nter Home, at 3213 Q street, by Solomon\nHeriog in honor of his late wife, was\ndedicated Bunday afternoon in the\npresence of a group of prominent local\nJewry.\nThe unveiling was performed by Mrs.\nGus Louis, and the dedicatory address\nwas made by Herbert Hollander, super\nintendent of the Sunday school of the\nhome. Isaac Nordlinger, president of\nthe Jewish Foster Home, accepted the\nmonument on behalf of the home.\nMr. Hollander and Mr. Nordlinger\nboth praised the life and work of Mrs.\nHerzog In the local community. More\nthan 100 people attended the ceremony.\nwaste of fuel through improper car\nburetton and imperfect combustion.\nThe \u201cMoto-Vlta,\u201d as exhibted by the\ninventor, weighs about a pound and a\nhalf and can be produced at a nominal\ncost. It consists of a thermo-couplet\n\"bridge\u201d of platinum and nickel wires\nso attached to the motor that the gases\nconstantly pass over It, recording auto\nmatically the percentage of unburned\n?:ases escaping and enabling the driver\no increase the quantity of air in the\nfuel mixture.\nOr. Hutchison described the instru\nment as \"an Infallible and Intelligent\nmeans of eliminating the guesswork of\ncarburetion,\u201d and said its valne had been\nproved in six months oi flying by his\nolder son,V&ck Hutchison, a transport\npilot.\nCapt. Hawks said he would lest the\ndevice an his flight to Memphis, yenn.,\nTlturrf*. H\nFEATURES CARDED\nFOR BENEFIT GAME\nDrill to Be Staged and Life-\nSaving Buoy Demonstrated\nSaturday.\nA monster drill evolution and a dis\nplay of the breeches buoy which has\nsaved thousands of lives from vessels\nstranded on the shores of America have\nbeen arranged as side attractions for\nthe foot ball game to be played Satur\nday afternoon at Griffith Stadium by\nthe Marines and the Coast Guards for\nthe benefit of the unemployed of the\nDistrict and for the President\u2019s cup.\nSome 600 Coast Guardsmen are com\ning to Washington from Boston, New\nLondon. New Yurt, Philadelphia, Balti\nmore and Norfolk to attend the game.\nThese men will come aboard the Coast\nGuard cutter Champlain and four Coast\nGuard destroyers. The vessels will tie\nup at the Washington Navy Yard late\nFriday or early Saturday morning, it\nwas announced today by Comdr. 3. 8.\nBaylis, United States Coast Guard, com\nmanding officer of the Coast Guard Re\nceiving Unit at New London, Conn., and\nin charge of the Coast Guard arrange\nments for the benefit game.\nMaJ. Gen. Smedley D. Butler of the\nMarine Corps, commanding the post at\nQuantico. Va., was in communication\ntoday with MaJ. David L. S. Brewster,\nMarine Corps athletic director, and\nplans were worked out for the Marines\u2019\nparticipation in the pre-game enter\ntainment.\nMarines Will Parade.\nAbout 1,200 Marines from Quantico\nwill come to Washington Saturday by\ntrain and form for a parade at Mary\nland avenue and Fifth street. They will\nbe joined by Marines from the Marine\nBarracks in Washington, and will pa\nrade up Sixth street to T street, east\non T street to Fifth and up Fifth to the\nstadium.\nAt the stadium the \u201cleathernecks,\u201d\nunder command of Gen. Butler, will\ngather on the foot ball playing field and\nform a large M, denoting the Marine\nCorps. The 200-piece Marine Band will\nplay \u201cSemper Fidelia.\u201d and then the\nwhole contingent of \"devil dogs\u201d will\nsing the Marine campaign song, \u201cFrom\nthe Halls of Montezmua.\u201d Then the\nMarines will form a nuge C. G. as a\ntribute to their gridiron foes.\nNext will come a tribute to President\nHoover, with the Marines executing an\nintricate drill to form an \u201cH\u201d while\nthe Marine Band plays the Stanford\nUniversity march, the song of the Preai\ndent\u2019s alma mater. Then the custo\n-1 mary \u201cHall to the Chief\u201d will be played\nfor the President.\nThe breeches buoy drill, a demonstra\ntion of how this life saving device is\nr used to save sailors on ships stranded\nat sea, will be one of the pre-game\nfeatures, A line will be strung from a\n1 pole in the stadium to a point near\nthe President\u2019s box. and the breeches\nbuoy will bring a man down the line.\nThe little cannon used to shoot the\nline to stranded vessels will be on\ndisplay, but will not be shot.\ni Guards to March on Field.\nComdr. Baylis said today that each\nof the ships coming to the Capital for\nthe game would carry as many addi\ntional men as could be accommodated,\naside from their regular crews. The\n1 Guardsmen will form at the ball park\nand march on the field. If the Presl\n-1 dent has arrived by that time they will\noffer him a salute. If not, they will\nmarch in review before Rear Admiral\nFrederick C. Billard, commandant of\n1 the Coast Guard.\ni The band from the Coast Guard\nAcademy, New London, Conn., the in\n-5 stitution that turns out the officers of\nthe Coast Guard, win furnish music for\nthe Coast Guard contingent.\nIsaac Gans, chairman of the special\ncommittee taking care of disabled war\nveterans who are anxious to attend the\ngame, again asked all persons who buy\ntickets, but who do not intend to use\nthem, to turn them over to him so they\nmay be used by disahled veterans. The\n1 game committee will provide busses\u2019to\ntake the veterans from Walter Reed,\nMount Alto and the Navy Hospitals.\nThe Veterans of Foreign Wars Over\nseas Band, of 140 pieces, the largest\n1 veterans\u2019 musical organization in the\nworld, will also furnish music for the\ngame. The band is representative of\nthe eight posts of the Veterans of For\neign Wars in the District and will be\nled on the field Saturday afternoon by\nHonorary Col. Thelma Bonini and her\nbullpup mascot, Hotsy Totsy, with\nt William E. Freeman as drum major.\nThe band, in bright uniforms, will lend\nanother splash of color to what prom\nr ises to be a colorful throng.\n1 Boxes Will Be Decorated.\nThe boxes of the foreign diplomats\nwho will attend the game will be dec\norated with the flags of those countries\nand the Marine Band, between the\nhalves, will play each country\u2019s na\ntional anthem.\nThe Committee on Employment, co\nsponsor of the game with the Washing\nton Chamber of Commerce, will become\nan employer on its own behalf in an\neffort to advertise the game.\nThe committee will employ 28 men\nfrom the District Employment Bureau,\n480 Louisana avenue, and put sand.\nwich placards on them and send them\nalong a downtown route at 15-minute\ni intervals.\nNewbold Noyes, chairman of the\nGeneral Benefit Game Committee, today\nannounced that the distribution of box\nseats for the game will take place\nThursday.\nAdditional boxholders were listed, as\nfollows: Assistant Secretary of War\nfor Aviat'on F. Trubee Davison; Mrs.\nJohn A. Wilkinson, Mrs. Borden Har\nriman, Civil Service Commissioner\nJessie Dell, the Minister of the Nether\nlands, J. H. Van Royen: Representa\ntive Sol Bloom, the Belgian Ambassa\ndor, Prince Albert de Ligne; the French\nAmbassador. Paul Claudel, and the Nic\naraguan Minister, Dr. Don Juan B.\nSacasa.\nMembers of the House today were\nurged to attend the game when the\nSpeaker read a letter from Chairman\nNoyes.\nRepresentative William P. Holaday of\nIllinois also sent to every member of the\nHouse a letter urging attendance at the\ngame, in which he said that \u201cit is ex\npected that the House will adjourn over\nthe week end and the committee has ex\npressed the hope that the membership\nof the House and Senate will attend the\ngame.\u201d Representative Holaday. in ex\nplaining the contest to his colleagues,\nsaid:\n\u201cThe game Is to be held to provide a\nfund for relief of the unemployed in\nthe District of Columbia. It will bo\nattended by the President of the United\nStates, the Vice President, the Speaker\nof the House of Representatives, the\nChief Justice of the Supreme Court, a\nmajority of the membership of the Cab\ninet and many of the diplomatic corps.\"\nMr. Holaday\u2019s letter notifies the House\nmembers they can obtain tickets\nthrough the sergeant-at-arms of the\nHouse and that the delivery will be\nmade Thursday. He also emphasized\nthat sections of the stand are to be re\nserved so that members of the House\nand their guests will be seated to\ngether.\nBAND CONCERT..\nBy the United States Soldiers\u2019 Home\nBand Orchestra, this evening, at Stan\nley Hall, at 5:30 o\u2019clock. John Zim\nmcnnann,. bandmaster; Anton Pointner,\nassistant:\nMarch, \u201cCivilization,\" Sca*rxin,twr\nOverture, \u201cFingals Cavem\u201d.Mendelssonn\nEntr\u2019acte\n\u201cCoralito\u201d Capa to\n\u201cConchita\u201d Stoughten\nExcerpts from musical comedy \"Fifty\nMillion Frenchmen\u201d Porter\n(Introducing the Barbershop QuariH.)\nWaltz, \u201cBlossom Time\u201d.....;. Romberg\nFinale, \"Cotton Pickin\u2019 TU\u00bb\nAlnbam\u2019 Dai/\n\u201cThe Star Spangled Banner.\"\nA","height":"25437","width":"19683"}}
